I made this for a work function and it was devoured. Great recipe. After reading a few reviews I decided to modify baking directions from another cheesecake recipe I had. I baked the cheesecake at 350F in a water bath for 1hr 10min, and the consistency was perfect. Also I suggest gradually adding the coffee/espresso mix to the cheesecake batter, tasting as you go, this gives you better control of the overall flavor.

Rating: 4
This is amazing cheesecake! I made it for a coworkers birthday and it was a huge hit. I'm not sure why the others reviewers felt it necessary to dilute the chocolate swirls with the cheese mixture. I love that part. My swirls did not get too hard in the fridge. I did swirl extensively. There were no clumps so that might make a differnce. I baked it at 400 for 44 minutes because I was worried about it not setting up but it did. It looked just like described with puffy slightly cracked edges and a golden top. Go ahead and add all the coffee. I made it with a homemade oreo crust. Fabulous!

Rating: 4
I've been making this cheesecake for many years now and it never disappoints. Everyone loves it! The only change I make is adding about a cup or a little more of the cheese mixture to the melted chocolate. Then swirl it in to the rest of the espresso cheese part. I find it melds better with the whole cake that way. I never add the coffee grounds because I find the coffee flavor to be strong enough and since I'm always raiding the left overs in the evening, I want to be able to go to sleep after that!

